durio@ix.netcom.com (Robert Durio) writes:

>SCSI vs IDE is like Windows/DOS vs Unix. True, Unix, from a technical 
>standpoint, is superior. However, since it is so egg-headish, clunky, 
>hard-to-use, and without application support, it will never go anywhere. 

It depends what you mean by "go anywhere". Yes, IDE is like Windoze/DOS:
it is cheap and nasty. The average PC buyer has no idea what good hardware
is, so they buy what is cheapest. Beyond that, the real reason why Unix
machines, Macs, Amigas and virtually every other computer system use SCSI
is that it is efficient and performs well in a multi-tasking environment.
DOS/Windoze users just throw more CPU power at a job, when a 386 with a
SCSI drive might actually be able to run some of their apps faster, if
Windoze had any way to use it properly.

Now that NT and OS/2 are around and Win 95 is on the horizon, the playing
field has changed, as ordinary users can now have operating systems
which can multi-task properly.

>IDE dominates and will always 
>dominate until the next interface comes along. 

IDE will probably continue to dominate the lowest end of the market, the
same way that 16450 UARTs still dominate over the 16550 ... just because
they are a little cheaper.

