Please, with due respect to the never-ending religious flame wars over
DOS/UN*X, let's not try to make this issue into one of religion. Can
you explain clearly and concisely what in your experiences (not just
perceptions) leads you to claim that SCSI is "egg-headish, clunky,
hard-to-use"? I have both IDE and SCSI in my system and the SCSI side
could not have been easier to set up: set ID/termination, plug in and
away we go. How is that so hard? Contrast this to the problems (and
decreased performance) you get when you try to set up a master-slave
arrangement for two of the older generation IDE drives (and there are
still a lot of these around). BTW, the DAT drive I purchased over a
year ago for my system is still not available with IDE interface.

>SCSI, from a technical standpoint, is "superior", but except in 
>extremely demanding environments, such as a file server, its "egg-head" 
>characteristics, combined with additional cost, renders it a 
>non-solution for the mainstream user. IDE dominates and will always 
>dominate until the next interface comes along. 

I would submit that SCSI and its successors are suitable candidates
for this. The cost difference between IDE and SCSI hard drives is now
negliglible, and many new motherboards are coming with low cost SCSI
interface built in (BIOS support is getting better too).

I wish people would actually try to be more practical/technical and
less visceral when it comes to computer equipment.


Regards,
Paul Yee

P.S. So what exactly do you mean by the "egg-head" characteristics of
SCSI? I guess that makes all Apple users "egg-head" since they
exclusively use SCSI for hard disks and such.

